---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro'

const post = {
  title: 'Plastisol vs Water-Based Ink for Workwear: What Holds Up on a Vegas Job Site',
  description:
    'A practical breakdown of plastisol vs water-based ink for construction crew apparel in Las Vegas. Durability, hand-feel, ink behavior on cotton vs poly, and which one to spec for which garment.',
  category: 'Decoration Methods',
  readTime: '9 min read',
  date: 'Apr 21, 2026',
  isoDate: '2026-04-21',
  image: '/images/generated/service-screen-printing.jpg',
  slug: 'plastisol-vs-water-based-ink-workwear',
}

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@graph': [
    {
      '@type': 'Article',
      headline: post.title,
      description: post.description,
      image: `https://bighornthreads.com${post.image}`,
      datePublished: post.isoDate,
      dateModified: post.isoDate,
      author: {
        '@type': 'Person',
        name: 'Steve Dodson',
        url: 'https://bighornthreads.com/about/',
        sameAs: ['https://www.linkedin.com/company/vp-promotions-vegas'],
      },
      publisher: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'Bighorn Threads', logo: { '@type': 'ImageObject', url: 'https://bighornthreads.com/images/logos/bighorn-logo-color.png' } },
      mainEntityOfPage: `https://bighornthreads.com/blog/${post.slug}/`,
    },
    {
      '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
      itemListElement: [
        { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: 'https://bighornthreads.com/' },
        { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'Blog', item: 'https://bighornthreads.com/blog/' },
        { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 3, name: post.title, item: `https://bighornthreads.com/blog/${post.slug}/` },
      ],
    },
  ],
}
---

<BaseLayout title={post.title} description={post.description} canonical={`https://bighornthreads.com/blog/${post.slug}/`} ogImage={post.image} type="article" publishedDate={post.isoDate}>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(schema)} />

  <article class="bg-navy-950">
    <header class="relative overflow-hidden border-b border-navy-800">
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-br from-navy-950 via-navy-900 to-gray-900"></div>
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-[radial-gradient(ellipse_60%_40%_at_50%_30%,_rgba(193,155,61,0.06),_transparent)]"></div>

      <div class="relative mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 pt-20 pb-12 sm:px-6 sm:pt-24 lg:px-8">
        <nav class="mb-6 font-mono text-xs text-gray-400" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
          <a href="/" class="hover:text-gold-400">Home</a>
          <span class="px-2">/</span>
          <a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-gold-400">Blog</a>
        </nav>

        <span class="mb-3 inline-block text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-500">{post.category}</span>
        <h1 class="mb-6 font-heading text-3xl font-bold leading-tight tracking-tight sm:text-4xl lg:text-5xl">{post.title}</h1>
        <p class="mb-8 text-xl leading-relaxed text-gray-300">
          The two ink families behind almost every printed work shirt in Vegas. Different chemistry, different feel, very different lifespan. Here's how to pick the right one for the job.
        </p>

        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-x-4 gap-y-2 border-t border-navy-800 pt-6 font-mono text-sm text-gray-400">
          <span class="text-gold-500">Bighorn Threads Team</span>
          <span aria-hidden="true">&middot;</span>
          <span>{post.readTime}</span>
          <span aria-hidden="true">&middot;</span>
          <time datetime={post.isoDate}>{post.date}</time>
        </div>
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 pt-10 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <img src={post.image} alt="Screen printing press laying plastisol ink onto a contractor work shirt" width="1200" height="675" loading="eager" class="w-full rounded-2xl border border-navy-800 object-cover shadow-2xl" />
    </div>

    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-16 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <aside class="mb-12 rounded-2xl border border-navy-700/50 bg-navy-900/40 p-6 lg:sticky lg:top-24">
        <h2 class="mb-4 font-mono text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-500">In this article</h2>
        <ol class="space-y-2 font-mono text-sm text-navy-200">
          <li><a href="#how-they-differ" class="hover:text-gold-400">1. How the two inks actually differ</a></li>
          <li><a href="#plastisol-pros" class="hover:text-gold-400">2. Why plastisol still dominates workwear</a></li>
          <li><a href="#water-based-pros" class="hover:text-gold-400">3. Where water-based wins</a></li>
          <li><a href="#by-fabric" class="hover:text-gold-400">4. Behavior by fabric (cotton vs poly)</a></li>
          <li><a href="#vegas-conditions" class="hover:text-gold-400">5. The Vegas heat factor</a></li>
          <li><a href="#decision" class="hover:text-gold-400">6. Decision tree by garment</a></li>
        </ol>
      </aside>

      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Most contractors don't ask which ink we're using. They ask the cost, see a mockup, and approve. That's fine — for tee orders going to a giveaway. It's not fine when those shirts have to survive 12 months of Vegas heat, sweat, and industrial laundering. The wrong ink will crack, peel, or fade in 3 months. The right one will outlast the garment.
      </p>

      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Here's the working contractor's breakdown of plastisol vs water-based ink — what each one is, where each one wins, and how to spec for your crews instead of getting whatever the shop defaults to.
      </p>

      <h2 id="how-they-differ" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">1. How the Two Inks Actually Differ</h2>

      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Both inks are pushed through a screen and onto fabric the same way. The chemistry is what changes.
      </p>

      <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Plastisol</h3>
      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        A PVC-based ink suspended in plasticizer. It doesn't dry — it cures. The ink sits on top of the fabric and locks when heated through a cure tunnel at 320°F. Once cured, it's essentially a flexible plastic film bonded to the shirt.
      </p>

      <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Water-based</h3>
      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Pigment + binder + water. The water evaporates during cure, leaving the pigment soaked into the fabric fibers themselves. It dyes the cotton instead of sitting on top of it.
      </p>

      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        That fundamental difference — sits on top vs sinks in — drives almost every pro and con of each method.
      </p>

      <h2 id="plastisol-pros" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">2. Why Plastisol Still Dominates Workwear</h2>

      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Eighty percent of construction work shirts we print are plastisol. Here's why:
      </p>

      <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Opacity on dark fabric</h3>
      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Plastisol is fully opaque. A white logo on a navy tee looks white — bright, clean, no fabric showing through. Water-based on dark fabric requires a white underbase first, which adds steps and cost.
      </p>

      <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Color match precision</h3>
      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Pantone matching with plastisol is exact. We mix the ink to your brand color, run a swatch, and what you see on the press is what you get on every shirt. Water-based shifts slightly with fabric color and weave.
      </p>

      <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Wash durability</h3>
      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Properly cured plastisol holds up through 100+ industrial wash cycles. Construction laundering is brutal — high-heat, harsh detergent, often at a contracted FR laundry service. Plastisol takes that abuse better than almost any other decoration method.
      </p>

      <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Bold graphics</h3>
      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Big back prints, full-front graphics, bold type — plastisol delivers them with crisp edges and consistent ink lay. The opacity and ink film make the design read from across a job site.
      </p>

      <div class="my-10 rounded-2xl border-l-4 border-gold-500 bg-gold-500/5 p-6">
        <p class="mb-2 font-mono text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-500">Default for trades</p>
        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-100">
          For 80% of construction shirts — t-shirts, hoodies, hi-vis tees, hard-wearing daily kits — plastisol is the right call. It's loud, durable, and Pantone-precise.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 id="water-based-pros" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">3. Where Water-Based Wins</h2>

      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Water-based isn't a downgrade — it's a different tool. It wins clearly in a few specific scenarios:
      </p>

      <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Soft hand-feel</h3>
      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Because the ink dyes the fabric instead of sitting on top, water-based prints feel like nothing. Run your hand over a water-based tee and you barely feel where the print is. For premium or upscale-looking apparel — branded crew gear meant to feel "not work-shirty" — water-based wins.
      </p>

      <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Vintage / faded look</h3>
      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Water-based fades intentionally over time, in a way that reads as "lived-in" rather than "worn out." For brand-forward gear with that retro look (think craft beer or premium brand merch), water-based delivers an aesthetic plastisol can't.
      </p>

      <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Hot conditions, breathability</h3>
      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        A large plastisol back print on a tee creates a non-breathing zone — the ink film blocks air movement through the fabric. On a Vegas summer day, that matters. Water-based keeps the breathability of the original fabric. For crews running in 110° conditions, this is a real comfort difference on big designs.
      </p>

      <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Light fabric on light shirt</h3>
      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Water-based excels at light-on-light printing — gray ink on a white shirt, cream on natural cotton. Subtle tonal designs are where water-based looks better than plastisol can.
      </p>

      <h2 id="by-fabric" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">4. Behavior by Fabric: Cotton vs Poly</h2>

      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        This is where ink choice gets technical. The two inks behave very differently on the two main shirt fabrics.
      </p>

      <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">100% cotton</h3>
      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Both inks work, but water-based is at its best here. The cotton fibers absorb the pigment and lock it in. Plastisol works fine but doesn't have the soft-hand advantage.
      </p>

      <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">100% polyester (hi-vis, performance)</h3>
      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Plastisol only — but it has to be specialty plastisol with low-bleed additives. Standard plastisol on polyester causes dye migration: the polyester dye bleeds up into the cured ink and changes the color (white prints turn pink on red shirts, etc.). We use bleed-resistant inks specifically formulated for synthetics. Water-based does not work on polyester.
      </p>

      <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 font-heading text-xl font-bold">Cotton-poly blends (50/50, 60/40)</h3>
      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Plastisol with bleed-resistant additives. Water-based can work but the polyester portion of the fabric won't take the dye, leading to a mottled or patchy look. Most blended workwear gets plastisol.
      </p>

      <h2 id="vegas-conditions" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">5. The Vegas Heat Factor</h2>

      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Vegas changes the math on a few specific ink choices. Plastisol prints in 110° conditions can soften slightly when stacked or stored against another print — in extreme heat (a delivery truck baking in July), prints can transfer or stick. We've seen it happen on the worst days.
      </p>

      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Mitigations: cure plastisol at the upper end of the temperature range (340°F instead of 320°F) for full plasticizer cross-linking, and pack with absorbent paper between heavy prints. Shops that don't cure properly produce plastisol that softens in heat. We don't ship under-cured ink.
      </p>

      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Water-based has no heat issue — once dry, it's dye in the fabric and behaves like the fabric does. For shirts that will live in a service truck in July, water-based has an edge.
      </p>

      <h2 id="decision" class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">6. Decision Tree by Garment</h2>

      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Here's how we usually call it for crew apparel:
      </p>

      <ul class="mb-6 list-disc space-y-2 pl-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        <li><strong>Crew tees (cotton, daily wear)</strong> → plastisol if you want bold, water-based if you want premium</li>
        <li><strong>Hi-vis polyester</strong> → bleed-resistant plastisol (only option that works)</li>
        <li><strong>Cotton-poly blend tees</strong> → plastisol</li>
        <li><strong>Hoodies + crewnecks</strong> → plastisol on the chest, plastisol on the back, period</li>
        <li><strong>Premium brand merch (giveaways, recruiting)</strong> → water-based for the soft-hand premium feel</li>
        <li><strong>Polos</strong> → embroidery, not screen print at all (see <a href="/blog/screen-printing-vs-embroidery-construction/" class="text-gold-500 underline hover:text-gold-400">screen vs embroidery breakdown</a>)</li>
        <li><strong>FR shirts</strong> → FR-rated specialty inks only, separate conversation</li>
      </ul>

      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        For the full breakdown of how we print, see our <a href="/services/screen-printing-las-vegas/" class="text-gold-500 underline hover:text-gold-400">screen printing service page</a>. We carry plastisol, water-based, discharge, and athletic-grade inks — and we choose the right one based on the garment, the conditions, and how the gear will be used.
      </p>

      <div class="my-12 rounded-2xl border border-gold-500/30 bg-gold-500/5 p-8 text-center">
        <h3 class="mb-3 font-heading text-2xl font-bold text-white">Want a recommendation on your specific gear?</h3>
        <p class="mb-6 text-base text-gray-300">Send the garment + your design. We'll tell you which ink fits and why.</p>
        <a href="/contact/" class="inline-flex min-h-[48px] items-center gap-2 rounded-lg bg-gold-500 px-7 py-3 text-base font-bold text-navy-950 transition-all hover:bg-gold-400">Get a Quote</a>
      </div>

      <h2 class="mt-12 mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">The Short Version</h2>
      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Plastisol for daily-wear workwear, hi-vis polyester, hoodies, and any time bold opacity matters. Water-based for premium brand merch, soft-hand crew gear, and large back prints where breathability counts. Both, sometimes, on the same crew — different garments, different jobs.
      </p>
      <p class="mb-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-navy-200">
        Most shops only run one. We carry both. The right answer depends on the garment, not the shop's default.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-16 rounded-2xl border border-navy-700/50 bg-navy-900/40 p-6">
        <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
          <div class="flex h-14 w-14 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full border border-gold-500/30 bg-gold-500/10">
            <span class="font-mono text-lg font-bold text-gold-500">BT</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="mb-1 font-heading text-lg font-bold text-white">Bighorn Threads Team</p>
            <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-navy-200">Screen printing for Vegas trades since 2010. <a href="/services/screen-printing-las-vegas/" class="text-gold-500 underline hover:text-gold-400">See our full screen printing service.</a></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <section class="border-t border-navy-800 bg-navy-900/60 py-16">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 text-center sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <h2 class="mb-4 font-heading text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">Need print that holds up in Vegas heat?</h2>
      <p class="mb-8 text-lg text-gray-400">Plastisol, water-based, and FR-safe inks. We pick the right one for your job.</p>
      <a href="/contact/" class="inline-flex min-h-[44px] items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-gold-500 px-8 py-4 text-lg font-bold text-navy-950 transition-all hover:bg-gold-400">Get a Free Quote</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
